The 'Adirondack Park' is a publicly protected, elliptical area encompassing much
of the northeastern lobe of Upstate New York, United States. It is the largest
park and the largest state-level protected area in the contiguous United States,
and the largest National Historic Landmark.

The park covers some , a land area roughly the size of Vermont and greater than
the National Parks of Yellowstone, Yosemite, Grand Canyon, Glacier, and Great
Smoky Mountains combined.
